quote: As “Joker” slow-walks us towards its eventual maelstrom of iniquity, it never spells out how we should feel about its titular character.
critic.name: Keith Garlington
publication.name: Keith & the Movies

quote: Joker is violent, raw, and hits closer to home than many are willing to admit.
critic.name: M.N. Miller
publication.name: Ready Steady Cut

quote: Phoenix's preparation for and commitment to this role honours Ledger and his other predecessors, with an exhausted physicality, contortionist and Gollum-gaunt.
critic.name: Cris Kennedy
publication.name: The Canberra Times (Australia)

quote: The Joker is a powerful idea about accountability in our society but it's clear the script wasn't there. Luckily they were able to make it work with improv and interpretive dance.
critic.name: Alachia Queen
publication.name: Alachia Queen

quote: It's less a genuinely transgressive approach than one closely modeled on the work of Martin Scorsese, and thus more an exercise in homage than rebellion. Even so, that won't stop people from aggrandizing it.
critic.name: Brian Eggert
publication.name: Deep Focus Review

quote: Every decade has that one transcendent film that, as time progresses, ultimately becomes a classic for cinephiles. As the 2010s decade comes to a close, the one film that will undoubtedly age like a fine wine is Todd Phillips masterpiece, Joker.
critic.name: David Gonzalez
publication.name: Reel Talk Inc.

quote: As committed as I was to Phoenixs performance, I found myself walking out of the theater wondering, why did we need to tell this deeply violent and triggering story now? Where does DC go from here and this standalone film?
critic.name: Kay-B
publication.name: The Beat

quote: "Joker" a lovely homage to films of a previous era and a subversive take on the "formula" of superhero/comic-book media.
critic.name: Don Shanahan
publication.name: Cinephile Hissy Fit Podcast

quote: If cinema's job is to make us feel, to make us reflect upon how we've been living life, and to acknowledge some of its own brand of crazy, then I think Joker did a damn good job.
critic.name: Nicholas Oon
publication.name: Maximum Hype (YouTube)

quote: It's a disappointing film only because it could have been so much better.
critic.name: Maria Lattila
publication.name: Shuffle Online

quote: [Phoenix as the Joker] burns like he were an archangel on heroin, a contorted otherworldly presence that under a different constellation of stars would have ended up a saint.
critic.name: Milana Vujkov
publication.name: Lola On Film

quote: Ultimately, Joker is neither deserving of the controversy it's stirred up nor some of the praise it's received. Phoenix's performance is the highlight of what is ultimately a relatively tame film.
critic.name: Collier Jennings
publication.name: But Why Tho? A Geek Community

quote: An instant classic that sees Joaquin Phoenix translate a discombobulating sensation from the screen to your senses, while director Todd Phillips creates a melancholic psychodrama...
critic.name: Greg Wetherall
publication.name: NME

quote: A male rage manifesto with ugly societal truths.
critic.name: Tony Black
publication.name: We Made This

quote: Although it has some of the hallmarks of a mainstream movie, there's little that's entertaining about Joker. Phoenix's version of the character is uncomfortable, and his off-putting nature will likely not inspire many repeat viewings.
critic.name: Alex Bentley
publication.name: CultureMap

quote: It may not be a deep or realistic study of mental illness but it showcases Arthur's weariness at being treated as the cigarette butt under society's heel.
critic.name: Richard Crouse
publication.name: Richard Crouse

quote: Joker is nothing more than a shallow homunculus of better films.
critic.name: Jeffrey Zhang
publication.name: Strange Harbors

quote: Phoenix gives the performance of his career, one already filled with admirable, transformative performances. But this one is different. This one is his cry for Oscar gold, and the masses will surely be chanting his name and singing his praises on high.
critic.name: Candice McMillan
publication.name: Seattle Refined

quote: ... this is an R-rated origin story for one of the most deranged, murderous villains in fiction, and the film reflects that. It may not make you feel good, but it will make you feel something, and sometimes that's enough.
critic.name: Mark Cassidy
publication.name: ComicBookMovie.com

quote: Surely the most realistic depiction of a supervillain becoming a supervillain thus far.
critic.name: Mike Massie
publication.name: Gone With The Twins

quote: Joker is a subversion of the trope of the hero's journey, made for a villain.
critic.name: Shah Shahid
publication.name: Blank Page Beatdown

quote: Without Mr. Phoenix, Joker would be kind of dull.
critic.name: Robert Slack
publication.name: SooToday.com

quote: Joker is repulsive, cynical garbage that tries acting more meaningful than it actually is.
critic.name: Matthew St. Clair
publication.name: Cinema Sentries

quote: Joker is a one-man show...the riot scenes near the end of Joker reflect something true in society, and they brought the film out of its shell.
critic.name: A.S. Hamrah
publication.name: The Baffler

quote: It's one of 2019's most unforgettable cinematic experiences.
critic.name: Richard Propes
publication.name: TheIndependentCritic.com

quote: A comic book movie with sufficient creative liberty to become a psychological thriller that talks about the darkest feelings of human reality. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Victor Pineyro
publication.name: Seventh Art Studio

quote: Repellent and pitiful at the same time, Phoenix is absolutely riveting.
critic.name: Jason Best
publication.name: Marie Claire

quote: Phillips constructs a palpable sense of down-and-dirty dread, helped by Phoenix's commitment ... but the movie stops short of ever expressing an opinion.
critic.name: Tom Beasley
publication.name: VultureHound

quote: The curveballs that Joker will throw at you stay in your head for hours afterwards, as does the haunting collapse of its protagonist.
critic.name: James Hanton
publication.name: Outtake Mag

quote: It all reminds me of a Goth teenager: He dresses in black, circles his eyes with mascara and mopes around in his room, all the time with no idea what he's so depressed about.
critic.name: Bill Newcott
publication.name: The Saturday Evening Post

quote: Don't expect a Marvel action flick for kids. This is a gritty character study, one where fans and critics can all agree on one thing: Joaquin Phoenix could laugh all the way to the Oscars.
critic.name: Jason Fraley
publication.name: WTOP (Washington, D.C.)

quote: Undeniably compelling.
critic.name: Saibal Chatterjee
publication.name: NDTV

quote: While drawing heavy influence from previous Scorsese movies, Joker boasts a great performance from Phoenix and shows that darker comic book films continue to have a place in a family-oriented realm.
critic.name: Murjani Rawls
publication.name: Deadscreen

quote: What an electrifying performance by Phoenix ... It's the work of a fearless performer, and the result is an acting masterclass.
critic.name: Allen Almachar
publication.name: The MacGuffin

quote: Phillips and Phoenix deliver a shattering and fresh new take on an age-old character, a character study of the birth of the supervillain with darkly disturbing vigour.
critic.name: Zehra Phelan
publication.name: Flavourmag

quote: Joker  is dark, dense, violent, and monstrous. A descent into Hades that is unlike anything we've seen on screen that's inspired by a comic [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Luis Bond
publication.name: A Simple Vista

quote: Has nothing to say about the issues it raises, so they come across like mere window dressing to what's in the end a fairly conventional comic book supervillain origin story.
critic.name: Adam Lubitow
publication.name: Rochester City Newspaper

quote: Well I just saw the feel-good movie of the year. Yikes!
critic.name: Doug Walker
publication.name: Channel Awesome

quote: I have no doubt for a second that Phoenix's performance is one of the most complex of the year. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Yasser Medina
publication.name: Cinemaficionados

quote: Joker is a brilliantly executed melancholy exploration of mental illness, anchored by a riveting performance from [Joaquin] Phoenix.
critic.name: Damond Fudge
publication.name: KCCI (Des Moines, IA)

quote: Even when Joker ventures into morally murky territory, it feels grimly realistic.
critic.name: Alex Hudson
publication.name: Exclaim!

quote: It made me think, it made me feel, it had a powerful performance at its core.
critic.name: Avaryl Halley
publication.name: Movie Bitches

quote: It's a good but deeply affecting movie.
critic.name: Andrew Galdi
publication.name: Movie Bitches

quote: You got to hand it to Joaquin Phoenix for fully inhabited his role of a loner on the verge of psychological breakdown in "Joker".
critic.name: Casey Chong
publication.name: Casey's Movie Mania

quote: For all the hype and anxiety surrounding the film, one can't help but walk away asking, all of that noise for this?
critic.name: Andrew F. Peirce
publication.name: The Curb

quote: Joaquin Phoenix, in another outstanding performance.
critic.name: Ben Sachs
publication.name: Chicago Reader

quote: It's disingenuous and pandering for Phillips to root through a grab bag of resentments and pick out only the least problematic, like he's trying to find the last candy in the bag that isn't licorice.
critic.name: Mark Asch
publication.name: Hyperallergic

quote: JOKER is a beautiful but simplistically shallow tale of one man's downward spiral, tacked on to a recognisable cinematic icon. Todd Phillips's film is a Batmobile with the engine of a clown car.
critic.name: Jim Ross
publication.name: TAKE ONE Magazine

quote: The more I watched it, the more I disliked it. Just did not work for me, I hate this movie.
critic.name: Shawn Edwards
publication.name: Fox 4 Kansas City

quote: The whole damn thing is directed with such boldness and vision that Todd Phillips (yeah, the Hangover guy) should never look back again. A big-screen must see.
critic.name: Stephen Rebello
publication.name: Playboy Online

quote: Not only an intelligent throwback to the feel-bad shock cinema of the 1970s, Joker is all but unique in its social realism...
critic.name: J. Hoberman
publication.name: Tablet

quote: Cinema is dead. Here is your proof.
critic.name: Cole Smithey
publication.name: ColeSmithey.com

quote: For just over two hours we are forced into alignment with a monster. And, not only that, it wants us to unrepentantly side with him. It feels hyperbolic to say that this results in a terrible sense of inescapable unease when watching, but it's the truth.
critic.name: Charlotte Harrison
publication.name: cultbox

quote: For what it is, it's gorgeously assembled, with a ragged jewel of a performance by Joaquin Phoenix at its center. The problem is, well, what it is... "Joker" ends up repeating itself and lap-dancing its same handful of nihilistic points again and again.
critic.name: Rob Gonsalves
publication.name: Rob's Movie Vault

quote: Ultimately, Joker blames society for its "hero's" unraveling, letting this maniac off the hook. Simplistic, yes. Reckless, undoubtedly. But not totally invalid.
critic.name: Jorge Ignacio Castillo
publication.name: Planet S Magazine

quote: ...A lethally dull and spiritually deadening exercise whose strained black humor and self-importance makes even the profundities of Christopher Nolan's Dark Knight trilogy feel meaningful by comparison.
critic.name: Chris Barsanti
publication.name: Eyes Wide Open

quote: I implore you: move on from Joker. You are better than this. We all are.
critic.name: Grant Watson
publication.name: Fiction Machine

quote: His story wasn't interesting to me because there never was a valid option for him to chose a different path.
critic.name: Rachel Wagner
publication.name: rachelsreviews.net

quote: Is it good? Parts of it. Did I enjoy it? Not really.
critic.name: Vera Wylde
publication.name: Council of Geeks

quote: Todd Phillips creates a terrifying masterpiece and one of the best and most daring comic book films ever made.
critic.name: Mina Takla
publication.name: AwardsWatch

quote: To celebrate "Joker" as the best of the year is akin to telling your friends of all the celebrities you met while walking through Madame Tussauds. It isn't and you didn't.
critic.name: Derek Deskins
publication.name: Edge Media Network

quote: an original thought-piece that builds on the dissonance of the past as a way to conjecture about the future.
critic.name: Andrea Chase
publication.name: Killer Movie Reviews

quote: Joaquin Phoenix gives one of the most memorable performances of the year and of his career in Todd Phillips' Joker.
critic.name: Lauren Veneziani
publication.name: WBAL-TV (Baltimore)

quote: I've seen or read so many types of Joker stories with so many types of Jokers that I can't possibly be shocked or bothered by what happens in the story, but I can say that everyone involved made a good film
critic.name: Julian Lytle
publication.name: idobi.com

quote: When he finally does put on the colourful suit and painted face, it's akin to watching a horror movie monster emerge.
critic.name: Damian Levy
publication.name: Jamaica Gleaner

quote: Fear of the masses - in a movie. And a bold, startling when not mournful expression of simmering low wage police state millennial generation misery.
critic.name: Prairie Miller
publication.name: WBAI Radio

quote: Phoenix overcomes the self-pity inherent in the material; he gives Arthur a sweet soul, and makes it hard not to like him, and to cringe when you see his next humiliation coming. In that sense, Joker is compelling.
critic.name: M.V. Moorhead
publication.name: Phoenix Magazine

quote: Joker is dark enough that you'll appreciate stepping out of the theater and into the light.
critic.name: Kirk Baird
publication.name: Toledo Blade

quote: A visceral, disturbing, but empathetic celebration of revenge.
critic.name: Kent Turner
publication.name: Film-Forward.com

quote: This film is a Joker cosplay more than Joker. A cipher elevated to saviour by the disenfranchised and angry. It's not only a bad joke, but it's also a sad joke.
critic.name: Blake Howard
publication.name: Graffiti With Punctuation

quote: It's twisted, it's funny, it's disturbing, but beautiful.
critic.name: Steph Cozza
publication.name: Aggressive Comix

quote: What cannot be argued is that Phoenix has once again turned in an Oscar-worthy performance...
critic.name: Asher Luberto
publication.name: L.A. Weekly

quote: Joker is a decent movie. It has its strengths: Phoenix's tour de force performance and Hildur Guðnadóttir's score among them. But for all that, it's not really worthy of all the hand-wringing it's inspired.
critic.name: Pete Vonder Haar
publication.name: Houston Press

quote: Joker begs for understanding and kindness, of which there is hardly any in the film. Phoenix should finally win an Oscar for his performance. He is heartbreaking.
critic.name: Sr. Rose Pacatte
publication.name: St. Anthony Messenger

quote: The result of these creative decisions, however, is that whatever power Joker, as a pop culture icon, might wield, Joker, as a movie, feels toothless.
critic.name: Angie Han
publication.name: Mashable

quote: Joker is an uncomfortable film that focuses on the beautiful cinematography and subtle dialogue to reflect on symbolic meanings and deeper thought of an individual's sanity.
critic.name: Steven Redgrave
publication.name: Pop Culture Leftovers

quote: There are several outstanding moments, a particular favourite of mine being Fleck dressed in a red suit, full make up, dancing on the stairs to THAT song...
critic.name: Katie Hogan
publication.name: She Likes Movies

quote: Fleck is a literal amalgam of both Thalia and Melpomene, an intriguing interpretation that positions his internal tension as the source of Joker's madness.
critic.name: Neil Morris
publication.name: Chatham News + Record (NC)

quote: It's an incredibly heavy film. It's well done, but it's heavy and leaves the viewer feeling like they've just gone 10 rounds in a heavyweight boxing match. It's mentally exhausting and desperately dark.
critic.name: Amanda Greever
publication.name: The Daily Times (Tennessee)

quote: Grim, violent 'Joker' is no laughing matter.
critic.name: Linda Cook
publication.name: Quad City Times (Davenport, IA)

quote: Where did the Joker come from? What's up with the clown schtick? Is his mom named Martha? All these questions and more are answered definitively by director Todd Phillips and Joaquin Phoenix, and it only takes two ponderous hours.
critic.name: Chris McCoy
publication.name: Memphis Flyer

quote: The equal of Phoenix's villain: a nasty, masochistic piece of work possessed by the notion the world must heed its lone-wolf howl, even though it has nothing to say once given the platform.
critic.name: Isaac Feldberg
publication.name: Fortune

quote: Joaquin Phoenix who goes all in with another full-throttle performance full of intensity. It's not entertaining or wholly original in it's approach but it comes with a phenomenal performance.
critic.name: Paul McGuire Grimes
publication.name: KSTP-TV (St. Paul, MN)

quote: Joker doesn't understand its representation of violence because it doesn't know what to do with its politics, opting instead for a confused aestheticization of anarchy, all incendiary chants and masked malcontents thronging the streets.
critic.name: Violet Lucca
publication.name: Film Comment Magazine

quote: The film owes a great deal to Joaquin Phoenix's performance as Arthur. Phoenix uses his body as a weapon, even before the transformation into the Joker.
critic.name: Andrew Kendall
publication.name: Stabroek News

quote: Looking at Joker for a kind of microcosmic version of melodrama giving way in the end to something better, however inchoate, is absolute wishful thinking. But like I said before - it's the perfect Rorschach inkblot.
critic.name: Eileen Jones
publication.name: The Jacobin

quote: Phoenix supercharges this Martin Scorsese-lite polemic with a bombastic, electrifying portrayal of unyielding sympathy for Arthur, whose desperation to connect with others descends into despair.
critic.name: Dann Gire
publication.name: Chicago Daily Herald

quote: The movie tells its story without apology, and Phoenix plays it to the serrated edge, conjuring a modern take on Milton's Paradise Lost, where we're asked to find sympathy for the devil after being cast out of heaven...
critic.name: Katherine Monk
publication.name: Ex-Press.com

quote: it is over before it begins because there is no other possible outcome than what we eventually arrive at, and Phillips and Silver don't give us an interesting enough trajectory to make up for that loss
critic.name: James Kendrick
publication.name: Q Network Film Desk

quote: If Arthur Fleck reflects the same cultural alienation that creates mass shooters and serial killers, the movie cuts away too often to establish a cogent argument.
critic.name: David Keyes
publication.name: Cinemaphile.org

quote: Todd Phillips can dump two cups of Taxi Driver into a bowl and slop in a cup and a half of The King of Comedy, but that doesn't make him Scorsese.
critic.name: Stuart Klawans
publication.name: The Nation

quote: It's hard to say if Joker entertains. It's dark and downbeat. There are good, even great, things about it, but overall it's just a little flat. It's one of those movies you can respect, though it's a little harder to like.
critic.name: Jeff Owens
publication.name: Enid Buzz

quote: Like "The Dark Knight", this film demonizes the mentally ill. It also distorts NY realities in the early 80s.
critic.name: Louis Proyect
publication.name: Counterpunch.org

quote: Even though it is most certainly not your traditional approach to this character. Definitely breaks ground.
critic.name: Carey-Ann Pawsey
publication.name: Orca Sound

quote: Heath Ledger's maniacal agent of destruction would have kicked this sorry-ass loser off Gotham's tallest building.
critic.name: Rubén Rosario
publication.name: MiamiArtZine

quote: Phoenix's mesmerizing lead performance is more than enough to carry the narrative past many of its meandering moments.
critic.name: Ian Thomas Malone
publication.name: Ian Thomas Malone

quote: Watching Joaquin dance and evolve is enough to make this movie worth the time. Unfortunately, the third act that reaches beyond the character is not as successful.
critic.name: David Poland
publication.name: Movie City News

quote: In the end, we think we know how his story goes but the surprise is on us. [Arthur is] becoming (yikes, and gulp) likable, and maybe that's the most disturbing part of Joker.
critic.name: Lapacazo Sandoval
publication.name: New York Amsterdam News

quote: If you're a die-hard Batman fan, some things are definitely going to throw you off. If you're a casual comic fan, the performance is great and all-around it was chilling and tense.
critic.name: Justin Brown
publication.name: Medium Popcorn

quote: Phoenix's performance is something we're still talking about, which is rare these days...I've just had a lot of conversations, still, about this movie.
critic.name: Brandon Collins
publication.name: Medium Popcorn

quote: I think this is a well-made movie... a well-acted movie. I think that it's not as deep as it sometimes thinks it is... but what helps it is Jaoquin Pheonix's performance.
critic.name: Andre Meadows
publication.name: Black Nerd Comedy

quote: In its depiction of Fleck's quixotic descent, Joker is as much about the spectators as it is about its tragic spectacle.
critic.name: Shaun McMichael
publication.name: PopMatters

quote: Even if blank despair and the inability of being funny is its topic, Joker never fails to please.
critic.name: Barbara Wurm
publication.name: Cinema Scope

quote: As a nightmarish portrait of urban isolation and a gritty comic book origin story, the movie is superbly acted and tensely paced. It also lacks nuance and plays into well-worn tropes. It's good. It's not great.
critic.name: Roe McDermott
publication.name: Hot Press

quote: Joker has a very important message about mental illness, and everyone should watch it. Maybe it will make people think twice about how they treat others.
critic.name: Tessa Smith
publication.name: Mama's Geeky

quote: But still: a provocation. Performance art. And an ongoing conversation.
critic.name: Ray Pride
publication.name: Newcity

quote: A study of descent into primal levels of reaction. Forget about superheroes. There are none to be seen in this version of Gotham. [Full review in Spanish].
critic.name: Federico Furzan
publication.name: Cinelipsis

quote: Joker is a jumble - sometimes brilliant and sometimes trite. Among its flashes of excellence is a self-serious movie that isn't nearly as deep as it thinks it is.
critic.name: Wenlei Ma
publication.name: News.com.au

quote: A disturbing and frightening origin story that reflects on sensitive issues that affect today's society. Joaquin Phoenix's bravura performance as the popular comic book villain is nothing short of extraordinary. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Rene Sanchez
publication.name: Cine Sin Fronteras

quote: Ugly, grotesque, depressing and yet quite fantastic...
critic.name: Felix Vasquez Jr.
publication.name: Cinema Crazed

quote: It's undeniably bleak to watch, but Phoenix demands our attention... and gets it.
critic.name: David N. Butterworth
publication.name: La Movie Boeuf

quote: Simply as a film, Joker leaves much to be desired: It's heavy-handed and derivative. But as with previous superhero narratives, it provides a fascinating allegory for present concerns.
critic.name: Jeet Heer
publication.name: The Nation

quote: The fundamental issue I have with Joker is that it's unnecessary.
critic.name: Edward Johnson-Ott
publication.name: NUVO Newsweekly

quote: Joker is a wicked trip.
critic.name: Tony Macklin
publication.name: tonymacklin.net

quote: Director Todd Phillips does not let up on the bleakness at any point. It is a film firmly grounded in humanity and ordinary and basic human vulnerabilities and needs in moments of challenge.
critic.name: Paula Fleri-Soler
publication.name: Times of Malta

quote: Digging deep into his role, Phoenix was the secret weapon required to make us understand the human pain behind Joker's wickedness.
critic.name: Filipe Freitas
publication.name: Always Good Movies

quote: Joker is a visual feast about mental illness, the crumbling of an unstable economic system, and toxic masculinity that thinks it has something groundbreaking to add to the comic book universe, but merely adds an obtuse reflection.
critic.name: Beth McDonough
publication.name: The Babbling Blonde

quote: Phoenix's Joker is a monster of his own making, and the film succeeds in blurring the lines between fantasy, reality, and hyper-reality, manipulating its audience to participate in the horror while challenging the individual's own mental soundness.
critic.name: Jerilyn Jordan
publication.name: Metro Times (Detroit, MI)

quote: Joker is a film to admire more than like. But it shouldn't be underestimated. It is a massively impressive, highly intelligent, openly provocative and ferociously performed masterpiece.
critic.name: Rob Carnevale
publication.name: Indie London

quote: Joker tries to be serious in a familiar genre, but hold on to the convention. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Alonso Díaz de la Vega
publication.name: El Universal

quote: Being one of the few Hollywood actors willing to risk, Phoenix makes the protagonist a man as repellent as fascinating. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Leonardo Garcia Tsao
publication.name: La Jornada

quote: Director without the artistic mastery of a Scorsese, but with capable to recognize the effectiveness of an incendiary speech on the screen in these times of social suspicion. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Carlos Bonfil
publication.name: La Jornada

quote: Brutally nihilistic and morally irresponsible, glamorizing and glorifying a nasty, maniacal villain, leaving one to wonder if a reel threat could inspire a real threat.
critic.name: Susan Granger
publication.name: SSG Syndicate

quote: Writer-director Todd Phillips and co-writer Scott Silver are taking societal problems that you might see explored in a Ken Loach film and bringing them into the superhero realm.
critic.name: Matthew Toomey
publication.name: ABC Radio (Australia)

quote: Joker offers enough to make it not a complete waste of everyone's talent, but the movie lacks that extra "wow" factor.
critic.name: EJ Moreno
publication.name: Flickering Myth

quote: If violence is a natural product of a community that is learning to take pleasure from hatred, Joker affords us a glimpse of the coming apocalypse.
critic.name: John McDonald
publication.name: Australian Financial Review

quote: Joker knows that its status as a property trumps secondary considerations like art and originality, but it purports to offer both under the safe and reassuring DC umbrella.
critic.name: Ed Whitfield
publication.name: The Ooh Tray

quote: The theatrical trailer for Joker -- tight, controlled, and intriguing -- suggested the best movie Martin Scorsese never made. The actual movie is a shallow and sophomoric effort that isn't about a raging bull as much as it's merely raging bulls***.
critic.name: Matt Brunson
publication.name: Film Frenzy

quote: A slow burn approach that delves into the psyche of the man who would become the Joker. It's an affecting and upsetting experience, but that's the point.
critic.name: Nicola Austin
publication.name: We Have a Hulk

quote: Phoenix is great, but the movie is a hack job.
critic.name: Bob Grimm
publication.name: Tucson Weekly

quote: It knew what it was doing. The performance is so intense, with just the right register for the film...hard-boiled cinema, it managed to do something new...
critic.name: Mark Kermode
publication.name: Kermode & Mayo's Film Review

quote: It's one of these movies with all the ingredients of a great movie, but manages to not be...the story editing, the film editing cut the legs out from so much of it. I admired it from a visual standpoint, but not feeling much of anything.
critic.name: Martin Thomas
publication.name: Double Toasted

quote: This was brilliantly-crafted cinema. The story falls in place naturally, with great performances all around to deliver that story, and gorgeous visuals.
critic.name: Korey Coleman
publication.name: Double Toasted

quote: Joker is a dread carnival, a relentlessly bleak tome of psychopathic origins that understands neither psychopathy nor origin stories.
critic.name: Jason McKiernan
publication.name: Film Racket

quote: Is it possible, in the world of 'Joker,' to believe in real heroism? Do the filmmakers even care about that question?
critic.name: Steven D. Greydanus
publication.name: National Catholic Register

quote: I feel like Joaquin [Phoenix] should get an Oscar nomination out of this, if not the win. Like for me, this is the best male performance of the year.
critic.name: Tony Baker
publication.name: Tony Baker Comedy

quote: Never evolves beyond scene after scene of painful slights, degradations, and worse - empty provocations.
critic.name: Adam Kempenaar
publication.name: Filmspotting

quote: A film that takes on the nigh-impossible task of smuggling transgressive underground danger into a contemporary, risk-averse multiplex tentpole package.
critic.name: Nick Pinkerton
publication.name: 4Columns

quote: The psychological journey of Arthur Fleck is interesting, but overall, I found this movie quite slow moving and predictable, despite a powerful performance by Phoenix. There is one surprise near the end, though.
critic.name: Robert Roten
publication.name: Laramie Movie Scope

quote: It keeps picking up enough of a queasy-making potency that it succeeds, sometimes quite well, despite the director's best intentions.
critic.name: Tim Brayton
publication.name: Alternate Ending

quote: We've been trolled.
critic.name: Cameron Williams
publication.name: The Popcorn Junkie

quote: For all the discourse around Joker, I was expecting something truly abhorrent - for better or worse. What I was shocked to find is how little of a bite it has.
critic.name: Karl Delossantos
publication.name: Smash Cut Reviews

quote: Joker turns nihilism into an Olympic sport, and given that aspiration, if that's even the right word, there was only one song worthy of the soundtrack.
critic.name: Rob Harvilla
publication.name: The Ringer

quote: Despite moments that feel like they're sincerely trying to warn us to about a world that creates Arthur Flecks, Joker often feels unchecked and unkempt in its unforgiving soapboxing and nihilistic, ugly tendencies.
critic.name: Cory Woodroof
publication.name: Nashville Scene

quote: [Joker] is aggressive in its unpleasantness, doubling and tripling down on its unreliability as it forces us to follow along on a journey where the line between reality and delusion is indelibly blurred.
critic.name: Allen Adams
publication.name: The Maine Edge

quote: Phoenix's maniac is never boring, always finding new layers of anguish; it's even remarkable what he does with the cigarettes he chain smokes.
critic.name: Richard von Busack
publication.name: MetroActive

quote: After talking some serious talk, it was up for debate if The Hangover director Todd Phillips could pull-off the challenge of making Joker.
critic.name: Niall Browne
publication.name: Movies in Focus

quote: Joker is a proceed with caution film, with an Oscar-worthy performance by Joaquin Phoenix.
critic.name: Sarah Knight Adamson
publication.name: Sarah's Backstage Pass

quote: A stunning example of comic-book filmmaking done with tangible grit and fearsome artistry.
critic.name: Matthew Pejkovic
publication.name: Matt's Movie Reviews

quote: As violent and as thematically dark as it often is, the film has moments of sheer brilliance and real bravery, especially when it comes to seeing the world from the point of view of somebody who is clearly deranged.
critic.name: Jim Schembri
publication.name: 3AW

quote: His archaic views about "PC culture" aside, Philips has created a pitch-black cinematic world where the have-nots have been pushed beyond the brink...brought forth from Phoenix a performance that will be studied as long as cinema exists.
critic.name: Donovan Farley
publication.name: Willamette Week

quote: Joker isn't a work of genius, it's not radical, bold, nor right-wing propaganda. It's just a movie, and a bad one.
critic.name: Millicent Thomas
publication.name: Screen Queens

quote: The role itself, fails to connect, feeling more like pomp and posturing than a real-world study of mental illness. But that's how it's meant to be. This is a comic book, after all: the real world should only seep in so far.
critic.name: Julie Crawford
publication.name: North Shore News (Vancouver, B.C.)

quote: All the references in Phillips's film don't feel like they're homages-they feel like blasphemy.
critic.name: Dom Nero
publication.name: Esquire Magazine

quote: The film isn't worth arguing over when it doesn't actually say anything at all.
critic.name: Gabrielle Bruney
publication.name: Esquire Magazine

quote: Gross isn't exactly a film-critic term. But then Joker isn't exactly a film. For one, it doesn't so much contain a plot as a series of brutal jolts to the senses. It doesn't so much contain characters as people who take and people who get taken.
critic.name: Stuart McGurk
publication.name: GQ Magazine [UK]

quote: It works not only because it's completely different to the average comic book movie, but also because it's an impeccably acted and directed drama. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Sebastian Zavala Kahn
publication.name: Cinencuentro

quote: The drama around Joker is overblown, mainly due to the media and people inserting messages in the film that aren't actually there.
critic.name: Chauncey K. Robinson
publication.name: The Twisted Girl Next Door

quote: With no huge plot surprises, it's another case of waiting for a film to make reveals you had figured out much earlier. Less "Ta-daa", more "Ta-duh".
critic.name: Jonathan Roberts
publication.name: The New Paper (Singapore)

quote: "...a provocatively toxic time capsule for an era of misguided rage."
critic.name: Josh Larsen
publication.name: LarsenOnFilm

quote: The elements really came together for this unique one-off.
critic.name: Rhys Tarling
publication.name: Isolated Nation

quote: Joker is effective art in the service of a worldview that endorses a double standard.
critic.name: Abbie Bernstein
publication.name: Assignment X

quote: Humorous elements do not appear to justify the criminal act or to alleviate it. They actually emphasize the grotesque character of the violence [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Rodrigo Garay
publication.name: Butaca Ancha

quote: Joker is replete with the signifiers of great cinema, all dialed up so heavily that they could denote parody if the film were not so serious.
critic.name: Forrest Cardamenis
publication.name: MUBI

quote: Joker indeed flourishes in abject vileness. It fetishizes the full extent of human savagery and rationalizes hate in a society that has become too crowded for its own good.
critic.name: Oggs Cruz
publication.name: Rappler

quote: ...a lamentably erratic endeavor that nevertheless fares better than most comic-book-inspired releases...
critic.name: David Nusair
publication.name: Reel Film Reviews

quote: Todd Phillips attempts to deliver a complex character study in the guise of a comic book film, but does so without any use of nuance or subtlety whatsoever.
critic.name: Kent Garrison
publication.name: Mad About Movies Podcast

quote: While Joker's ambition makes it interesting, it never follows through on the threads that deliver the most impactful messages.
critic.name: Alan French
publication.name: Sunshine State Cineplex

quote: In Joker, a suitably creepy lead performance by Joaquin Phoenix is undermined by heavy-handed direction and a clunky screenplay.
critic.name: Damien Straker
publication.name: Impulse Gamer

quote: A rather extraordinary movie... Ultimately, it is a study of the instability in the mind, the outer instability in the world, and what happens when those two things lay over each other in an extremely volatile way.
critic.name: Wade Major
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: A violent chaotic world beats down and then elevates a psychopath in this origin story. In the title role Joaquin Phoenix is brilliant. Even when the movie makes you want to turn your head he demands you keep your eyes on him.
critic.name: Jackie K. Cooper
publication.name: jackiekcooper.com

quote: For all the film's faults and manipulations, I was not bored for a second, and that is due to Phoenix, who gives his all as only he can.
critic.name: Alison Rowat
publication.name: The Herald (Scotland)

quote: The film is impressively lurid, with a freak-out performance from Joaquin Phoenix... But even as it feels very of-the-moment, the film is indulgent and rather too lurid to take seriously.
critic.name: Rich Cline
publication.name: Shadows on the Wall

quote: Joker is an effectively disquieting character study featuring a great Joaquin Phoenix performance that doesn't actually court any of the controversy it's received.
critic.name: Jack Blackwell
publication.name: One Room With A View

quote: It's a ripoff of the highest order, borrowing from greater filmmakers without the nuance or intelligence to make the entire enterprise worthwhile.
critic.name: Jourdain Searles
publication.name: okayplayer

quote: It's hypnotic just how horrifying Arthur's existence is, just as Phoenix's performance is hypnotic as he spirals from fragile hope into increasingly outsized and confident acts of destruction.
critic.name: Tasha Robinson
publication.name: The Verge

quote: It turns out the piece of art that has caused such an uproar is nothing more than an incoherent, misbegotten and embarrassingly dull two hours.
critic.name: Ani Bundel
publication.name: NBC News THINK

quote: It's unclear if the movie thinks that the Joker doesn't know that his statement is political, or the film itself doesn't understand it's own political nature[...]
critic.name: Emmet Asher-Perrin
publication.name: Tor.com

quote: As well made as Joker is, there is little here to delight in beyond Phoenix's performance.
critic.name: Lisa Kennedy
publication.name: AARP Movies for Grownups

quote: Joker is a soulless retread that hopes to masquerade in the flesh of a Martin Scorsese/Paul Schrader film in an attempt to seem edgy or dark but is ultimately defiantly mediocre at best and an utter sham at worst.
critic.name: Rob Dean
publication.name: Bullz-Eye.com

quote: A derivative movie that exploits mental illness and violence
critic.name: Chase Whale
publication.name: ChaseWhale.com

quote: There's a cowardice about all of this which is really hard to ignore.
critic.name: Michael Ward
publication.name: Should I See It

quote: Joker, on the other hand, feels like a damning indictment of societal ills, a study in how real monsters are made; it's a film that's desperately, maybe even depressingly relevant.
critic.name: Emma Simmonds
publication.name: Radio Times

quote: In aping the ambition and prestige of its motley influences, Joker winds up with a bungled understanding of its own relation to violence.
critic.name: Phoebe Chen
publication.name: Film Comment Magazine

quote: For all the handwringing over Joker's release to call it dangerous simply imbues it with more coherence and power than it actually has.
critic.name: Marisa Carpico
publication.name: The Pop Break

quote: A movie that borders on genius-repellant, dark, terrifying, disgusting, brilliant and unforgettable.
critic.name: Rex Reed
publication.name: Observer

quote: The filmic language that one can break down has an unambiguous achievement: to give the film the code of a classic epic and avoid the banality of a meaningless comic. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: William Venegas
publication.name: La Nación (Costa Rica)

quote: So intently focused as he is on crafting an edgy and grown-up vision of the Batman world, Phillips sacrifices consistent character development, good scripting and editing.
critic.name: Tom Augustine
publication.name: New Zealand Herald

quote: Whilst the movie lacks depth somewhat, it's undeniably haunting and unnerving - Phoenix is monstrously good in the titular role.
critic.name: Matt Hudson
publication.name: What I Watched Tonight

quote: Cinematography, art direction and Phoenix's performance are the draws here; the story is so derivative, drawn out, empty and vapid that the film's biggest fault is that it drags.
critic.name: CJ Johnson
publication.name: Film Mafia

quote: It's not a movie I'm likely to be watching again, but the visuals, atmosphere, and the lead performance are incredibly strong.
critic.name: Marianna Neal
publication.name: Impression Blend

quote: There's a moment when he crystalizes into the character, we see it coming, but it arrives with a monstrous sort of grace.
critic.name: Eli Glasner
publication.name: CBC News Network

quote: Brilliant. See it and there is no need to see any other film in 2019.
critic.name: Victoria Alexander
publication.name: Las Vegas Informer

quote: Not nearly as compelling as the weeks of controversy leading up to its release would indicate. It's both completely ridiculous and ill-conceived
critic.name: Stephen Silver
publication.name: Splice Today

quote: As a gritty comic book villain origin story Joker mostly works on its own merits, but when it tries to match Scorsese's righteous fury, it feels like little more than a pale imitation.
critic.name: Mattie Lucas
publication.name: From the Front Row

quote: {Joker} is one of Joaquin Phoenix's top five performances ever, one that is interesting, compelling and capable of carrying the entire film on its back...
critic.name: Dominic Griffin
publication.name: The Armchair Auteur

quote: 'Joker' is a slow-burn psychological thriller that often feels like it's hitting a little too close to home.
critic.name: Jonita Davis
publication.name: The Black Cape

quote: Joker is a better film the further writer/director Phillips stays away from the movie's comic book origins and hones in on Arthur's wavering grasp on sanity.
critic.name: Matt Ward
publication.name: Cinematic Considerations

quote: It's an appropriate film for its eponymous antagonist...repellent in its wanton depravity, it's still maddeningly captivating, and sure to spark strong reactions.
critic.name: Joel Mayward
publication.name: Cinemayward

quote: While I can't say I was entirely won over by Joker's thrall in itself, I also can't deny its achievements.
critic.name: Oscar Goff
publication.name: Boston Hassle

quote: Joker suggests that mental health issues require government funding-a narrative that would actually be progressive, if the film stopped there.
critic.name: Robert Daniels
publication.name: Mediaversity Reviews

quote: Less Falling Down and more Fight Club, an anti-hero discovers the power of invisibility, self-delusion, and murder before bringing all three to bear in choosing evil... it's a literal shot in the face that makes one think...
critic.name: Kevin A. Ranson
publication.name: MovieCrypt.com

quote: I can't say that Joker is a great film. Todd Phillips, Joaquin Phoenix, and the cast and crew have made a very good movie that's sure to polarize audiences and, like Fight Club, is sure to be misunderstood.
critic.name: Tim Brennan
publication.name: About Boulder

quote: The chilling take away I got is that the cackling laugh of the Joker gets into your head, as if the filmmaker thinks that's enough to explain this sad mental illness story.
critic.name: Dennis Schwartz
publication.name: Dennis Schwartz Movie Reviews

quote: Joker looks set to have the last laugh.
critic.name: Mark Kermode
publication.name: Observer (UK)

quote: It's admittedly hard to imagine a film like Joker inspiring real-world violence - or inspiring much of anything.
critic.name: Siddhant Adlakha
publication.name: Firstpost

quote: Joker is not challenging, daring or risky in the least, on the contrary, Phillips adheres with discipline to the rules of the now old New Hollywood and proves to be a docile student, not a visionary. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Jorge (JJ) Negrete
publication.name: Butaca Ancha

quote: Phoenix, an actor capable of overcooking a performance, gets it spot-on, delivering a tour de force.
critic.name: Matthew Bond
publication.name: The Mail on Sunday (UK)

quote: Phillips does everything except have someone holding up a placard reading "It's time to take the Joker seriously."
critic.name: Tom Shone
publication.name: Sunday Times (UK)

quote: The kind of rich, complex movie DC has been trying and failing to make ever since The Dark Knight Rises.
critic.name: Edwin Arnaudin
publication.name: Asheville Movies

quote: It's brazen rejection of subtext in favor of brash surface literalism is downright Samuel Fullerian.
critic.name: Nathanael Hood
publication.name: Nate Hood Reviews

quote: The crowning achievement of Joker, other than Joaquin Phoenix's acting, is the film's score. Hildur Guðnadóttir composed one of the most iconic scores of the year. It is not an understatement that her score made the film for me.
critic.name: Sarah Ksiazek
publication.name: The MacGuffin

quote: All the worst inflections of comic book origin fetish, dangerously misunderstanding complex themes from Scorsese's films, and glibly piggybacking on zeitgeisty social issues.
critic.name: PJ Nabarro
publication.name: Patrick Nabarro

quote: Much like the Joker himself, Joaquin Phoenix is a performance artist who uses audacity and shock as substitutes for depth.
critic.name: Karen M. Peterson
publication.name: Citizen Dame

quote: Joker is raw, unsettling, and experimental, anchored by an absolutely mesmerizing central performance.
critic.name: Zaki Hasan
publication.name: Zaki's Corner

quote: Joker is the perfect bogeyman for our age, embodying the toxic, corrosive power of an entertainment-obsessed, hyper-mediated society of spectacle.
critic.name: Brett McCracken
publication.name: The Gospel Coalition

quote: Bravo, and guess who'll have the last laugh when the Best Actor votes are counted.
critic.name: John Urbancich
publication.name: Your Movies (cleveland.com)

quote: The gritty look and dark tone of Todd Phillips' origins story is exactly the treatment needed for the sinister supervillain. With Scorsese overtones and Phoenix in one of his best performances classify this under Masterpiece.
critic.name: Joe Friar
publication.name: The Victoria Advocate

quote: While you're not going to see any capes or super-powers, certain allusions made only serve to take you out of the moment and muddy what the movie's true intentions are.
critic.name: Travis Hopson
publication.name: Punch Drunk Critics

quote: The Taxi Driver of comic book movies.
critic.name: Matt Neal
publication.name: ABC Radio (Australia)

quote: It's a piece of art; a dark, devastating yet mesmerising offering, in which Phoenix - whose magnetic and eerily graceful Joker hobbles and dances his way from mentally unstable loser to despicable murderer - gives the performance of a lifetime.
critic.name: Chris Wasser
publication.name: The Herald (Ireland)

quote: Joker is to Martin Scorsese what Battleship was to Michael Bay; an empty attempt at imitation that confuses aesthetics and homage for quality and flattery.
critic.name: Jennifer Heaton
publication.name: Alternative Lens

quote: ... no matter how much Phillips, Phoenix and the DC/Warner Brothers corporate brains trust want it to be some profound examination of masculine malaise, this too is just a comic book movie.
critic.name: David 'Mad Dog' Bradley
publication.name: Adelaide Review

quote: A multi-layered cautionary tale about the perils of living in a divisive, heartless urban jungle, the movie gains momentum midway and descends into a maelstrom of grotesque violence.
critic.name: Rashid Irani
publication.name: Hindustan Times

quote: I enjoyed the dark twists of Joker, mirrored by the twisting of Pheonix's body. But even with a masterful performance by Phoenix, I struggled with yet another attack on the origin of the comic villain I grew up with.
critic.name: Vincent Schilling
publication.name: Indian Country Today

quote: One of the best films of the year without a doubt. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: David Ocadiz
publication.name: Cinergética

quote: It's the same old song over and over again, a cultural record scratch. Send in the clowns...
critic.name: Kevin Fallon
publication.name: The Daily Beast

quote: Phoenix's take on the character, whose scars are all on the inside, might explain how a person gets that way. Beyond that, it's best to watch Joker under the assumption it's a one-off.
critic.name: Randall King
publication.name: Winnipeg Free Press

quote: Arthur Fleck's transformation to the enigmatic Joker ends up being a bucket of ice water for the viewer. Because what we see on the screen is no longer part of a fictional universe and instead becomes a reflection of reality. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Arturo Magaña
publication.name: Cine Premiere

quote: It falls short as an agent of chaos: because it has a reason, a story, an explanation, a cause ... but not a will. Despite this it ends well-enough and unsettling enough. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Hugo Hernández Valdivia
publication.name: Cinexcepción

quote: Essential. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Quim Casas
publication.name: Sensacine

quote: We get the monsters we deserve.
critic.name: Rob Vaux
publication.name: Sci-Fi Movie Page

quote: Joker is certainly an interesting and worthy experiment, bringing a dark, unrelenting nihilism to a genre that's built on morality.
critic.name: Annlee Ellingson
publication.name: L.A. Biz

quote: ...the most radical film to come from a major studio since Fight Club.
critic.name: Chris Gore
publication.name: Film Threat

quote: "Joker" is a character study laced with societal commentary, more art-house than blockbuster. And in a world of ready-made superhero franchises, it's so bold, it's shocking.
critic.name: Brad Keefe
publication.name: Columbus Alive

quote: What happens when a broken person is immersed in a broken environment. A question brilliantly asked by JOKER.
critic.name: John Campea
publication.name: The John Campea Show

quote: What should have been the most electrifying comic book picture of the year is actually one of its most shocking duds.
critic.name: Mike McGranaghan
publication.name: Aisle Seat

quote: Much of this great achievement as a director is due, no doubt, to the three-time Oscar nominee, Joaquin Phoenix, who delivers one of the best performances of his career. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Lucero Calderón
publication.name: Excelsior

quote: All the positive things you've heard about [Joaquin Phoenix] as the Joker are true. He is absolutely fantastic... That performance alone is worth the price of admission.
critic.name: Jaby Koay
publication.name: GET Jaby

quote: Joker is overly long, thematically murky and narratively uneven, with an unnecessary ending that, like a bad greasepaint job, ruthlessly highlights the film's flaws rather than concealing them.
critic.name: Brandy McDonnell
publication.name: The Oklahoman

quote: It is a deeply unpleasant movie. You'll walk away depressed, wondering if there's any good left in the world.
critic.name: Matt Miller
publication.name: Esquire Magazine

quote: One of the main problems I have with the film is its inability to decide what it wants to be.
critic.name: Beth Accomando
publication.name: KPBS.org

quote: By the time the movie is over, you will find yourself fully invested and ready to watch his journey continue. Well, if there's ever another one.
critic.name: Tatat Bunnag
publication.name: Bangkok Post

quote: Joker has two scenes that are absolutely brilliant.
critic.name: Stephen Garrett
publication.name: Book & Film Globe

quote: Intense and disturbing, Joker is a well-crafted movie, if rather open-ended in its intentions.
critic.name: Theresa Smith
publication.name: Weekend Special (South Africa)

quote: For me, The Joker is one of the top features released this year.
critic.name: Phumlani S Langa
publication.name: City Press (South Africa)

quote: Joker is a disturbing look through the eyes of a mad man who blames the world for his insanity, one told via career-best work from Todd Phillips and the performance of a lifetime by Joaquin Phoenix.
critic.name: Mark Goodyear
publication.name: Battle Royale With Cheese

quote: If there is a meaningful difference between performing and acting, Joaquin Phoenix surely exemplifies the former here, creepily contorting as the Clown Prince of Crime in Todd Phillips' timely, toxic take on the Making of a Murdering Madman.
critic.name: Matthew Lickona
publication.name: San Diego Reader

quote: This is probably the least comic-book "comic-book movie" ever, as writer/director Todd Phillips (with a writing assist from Scott Silver) shows us a bleak world devoid of heroes of any shape or form.
critic.name: Mathew DeKinder
publication.name: Suburban Journals of St. Louis

quote: Ultimately, Joker is near Shakespearean in its tragic scope. It's Macbeth for the comic book movie generation, and easily the most morally complex comic book film since The Dark Knight.
critic.name: Michael Lee
publication.name: Film Ireland Magazine

quote: Joker will grab you and hold you. Listen to it.
critic.name: Kelly Vance
publication.name: East Bay Express

quote: Phillips' flashes of style are all in service of a grimdark image rather than a message about the haves and have-nots, or the treatment of mental illness, or any of the other, real issues so easily within reach. It's all show, and no substance.
critic.name: Karen Han
publication.name: Polygon

quote: It's impossible not to feel empathy for this excruciatingly sad clown... Ultimately though, Joker fails because of its genre. The character has to hit those DC marks.
critic.name: Megan Basham
publication.name: WORLD

quote: Watching an emaciated creeper do several "kooky underpants dances" is definitely somebody's idea of a good time. It is just not mine.
critic.name: Ryan Syrek
publication.name: The Reader (Omaha, NE)

quote: As the title character, Phoenix is an unnerving ticking time bomb that slowly erupts on screen -- building to a explosive crescendo in the excellent final act.
critic.name: Micheal Compton
publication.name: Bowling Green Daily News

quote: [Phoenix] moves like a balletic contortionist spider, all limbs and big shoes and flapping bell-bottoms. When he explodes into full-bore killer clown mode, his release is not entirely monstrous; it's also heartbreaking.
critic.name: Jeffrey M. Anderson
publication.name: San Francisco Examiner

quote: Many moments in "Joker" are pretentious and derivative, but when Phoenix turns his dead eyes toward you, all you see is him and the nightmare scenario surging in his heart and mind.
critic.name: Bob Bloom
publication.name: Journal and Courier (Lafayette, IN)

quote: While it succeeds in aping the superficial aspects of [Martin] Scorsese's style, "Joker" lacks the intelligence or gravitas of Scorsese's best work.
critic.name: Matthew Rozsa
publication.name: Salon.com

quote: A dark, deranged and often mesmerizing take on the superhero genre. The sort of movie that crawls into your guts and stays there awhile.
critic.name: Christopher Lloyd
publication.name: The Film Yap

quote: Todd Phillips has made a surprisingly austere and relentlessly dark origin film. Arthur Fleck aka Joker is this generation's Travis Bickle.
critic.name: James Verniere
publication.name: Boston Herald

quote: Joker is a tough watch that is not entirely rewarding but is ambitious enough to swing for the fences when it sees the opportunity.
critic.name: Spencer Perry
publication.name: ComingSoon.net

quote: The film works as social awareness as much as it does as a performance vehicle for Joaquin Phoenix. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Emmanuel Báez
publication.name: Cinéfiloz

quote: "Joker" effectively tells a story with themes borrowed, but not stolen, from movies like "Taxi Driver" and "Network" and makes them its own platform through its own disturbed form of avenging angel.
critic.name: Michael Smith
publication.name: Tulsa World

quote: There's... a strong sense that Phillips is brandishing this bleakness as a kind of affect, like the rich kid who wears his brand new black leather jacket to a punk show but only after intentionally scuffing it against the grill of his Bentley first.
critic.name: Piers Marchant
publication.name: Arkansas Democrat-Gazette

quote: As an origin story it's rather compelling to see what drove the man down the path we know he has to eventually tread, and as a character study it's equally captivating to see the effects it has on the man himself.
critic.name: Jeff Beck
publication.name: The Blu Spot

quote: Joker is a self-serious movie that, in spite of its lead, posits itself as revolutionary when it never hovers above bland and tasteless.
critic.name: Kristen Lopez
publication.name: Culturess

quote: The most audacious comic-book-inspired film ever made; one that doubles-down on its depravity with no remorse. That said, it's impossible not to become hypnotized by its external beauty and indiscriminate brutality.
critic.name: Kiko Martinez
publication.name: San Antonio Current

quote: Joker is ultimately an-in-your face examination of a broken class system that creates its own monsters. It's a gritty and morbidly beautiful journey with little comfort to spare, but many messages to mull over.
critic.name: Chauncey K. Robinson
publication.name: People's World

quote: Joker is a captivating and insanely brilliant presentation of the classic comic book villain thanks to the award worthy performance by Joaquin Phoenix.
critic.name: Emmanuel Noisette
publication.name: The Movie Blog

quote: Phoenix's performance is monumental, a black hole of agony and despair that attracts everything else in the film towards him, consuming it in its deep and inescapable darkness. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Mario Alegre
publication.name: Próxima Tanda

quote: One of the most gratuitously grim films of the decade, you can't help but wonder for whom the film rolls.
critic.name: Lisa Johnson Mandell
publication.name: AtHomeInHollywood.com

quote: Joker is an impressive achievement on many levels, but the sloppy mixed message of the film and the near torturous dread of the entire outing leave very little entertainment to be had.
critic.name: Kyle Wilson
publication.name: The Lamplight Review

quote: It's dark, violent and unsettling, but it's also extremely thoughtful and executed to perfection. If you do choose to see it, it will stick with you for a long time.
critic.name: Josh Terry
publication.name: Deseret News (Salt Lake City)

quote: What Arthur is meant to represent or convey is a mystery only Phillips might understand, because all he evokes on screen is aimless pain, which many people do actually endure but should a film simply be despair for entertainment and nothing more?
critic.name: Alci Rengifo
publication.name: Entertainment Voice

quote: This is a fascinating movie, but I wouldn't call it fun.
critic.name: Chris Knight
publication.name: National Post

quote: A great work and an example of how great the comic-based cinema can be if it is risky enough, with the sole purpose of presenting a more complex, mature and rewarding proposal. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Iván Belmont
publication.name: Konexión

quote: Director Phillips, best known for the inane Hangover movies, wants to show he can be serious and profound, but has bitten off more than he can chew.
critic.name: Daniel M. Kimmel
publication.name: North Shore Movies

quote: A sour, incoherent jumble, redeemed only by Joaquin Phoenix's astonishing performance in the central role.
critic.name: Robert Horton
publication.name: HeraldNet (Everett, WA)

quote: The movie gets off to a strangely muted start, and even fans of the DC comics in which the demented clown has been giving Batman so much guff for the past 80 years may grow restless.
critic.name: Kurt Loder
publication.name: Reason Online

quote: This movie will hit you hard emotionally and also leave you conflicted over how you feel about the title character, who is considered one of Batman's biggest foes but also one of the most formidable villains in the entire comic-book universe.
critic.name: S. Indra Sathiabalan
publication.name: The Sun Daily (Malaysia)

quote: One of the best comic book movies of all-time, Joker takes us to some dark places but it's a richly rewarding (and haunting) experience which is anchored by an unbelievable performance from Joaquin Phoenix. It's a masterpiece.
critic.name: Josh Wilding
publication.name: ComicBookMovie.com

quote: Who knew that Phillips had this kind of haunting, violent and grime-encrusted effort in him?
critic.name: Robert Denerstein
publication.name: Denerstein Unleashed

quote: Carried by a commanding, Oscar-worthy performance by Joaquin Phoenix in the titular role, Joker explores the darkest aspects of society and offers a window into the mental breakdown of a man who is pushed passed his breaking point.
critic.name: Matt Rodriguez
publication.name: Shakefire

quote: A movie of a cynicism so vast and pervasive as to render the viewing experience even emptier than its slapdash aesthetic does.
critic.name: Richard Brody
publication.name: New Yorker

quote: Joker is a testament to the power of the right actor to elevate occasionally shaky material to a gold standard. Joaquin Phoenix's humanity-laden performance is the perfect mix of futility and fury.
critic.name: Aaron Peterson
publication.name: The Hollywood Outsider

quote: Certainly not for all audiences (especially kids), "Joker" is a master class in acting and seeing how and why evil can rise. (Full Content Review for Parents - Violence, Profanity, Nudity, etc. - also Available)
critic.name: Jim Judy
publication.name: Screen It!

quote: Bleak and juvenile
critic.name: Jordan Hoffman
publication.name: Guardian

quote: These "look what I'm doing here" scenes drag the film, but as long as you never take your eyes off Phoenix (and who could?), you're not likely to notice.
critic.name: Hope Madden
publication.name: Columbus Underground

quote: A disturbing but somewhat courageous portrait of someone who loses everything but somehow wins most victoriously - at least, in his mind. Uncomfortable and righteous.
critic.name: Bill Arceneaux
publication.name: Moviegoing with Bill

quote: Joker offers tremendous imagery and a top performance from Joaquin Phoenix, but it fails to drum up any strong themes or interesting statements, leaving it feeling empty.
critic.name: Nicolás Delgadillo
publication.name: Cultured Vultures

quote: Phoenix's performance of a lifetime yields a comic book film for the ages.
critic.name: Phil Villarreal
publication.name: ABC Tucson

quote: Featuring a tour-de-force performance by Joaquin Phoenix, Joker is a rare comic book film that actually surprises.
critic.name: David Harris
publication.name: Spectrum Culture

quote: ...the story sort of just happens, with violence, expertly built tension, and some truly gorgeous cinematography used to fill the air where a central theme would normally go.
critic.name: Matthew Dougherty
publication.name: The Filtered Lens

quote: Features a masterful performance by Joaquin Phoenix, almost on the level of The Master and You Were Never Really Here. [Full review in French]
critic.name: Kevin N. Laforest
publication.name: Extra Beurre

quote: A gritty, Very Serious, faux-provocative movie with nothing to say.
critic.name: Eric D. Snider
publication.name: Crooked Marquee

quote: Everything that captivates us about Arthur is inevitably forgotten and everything he becomes is beholden to familiar tropes. It does look great, but I left feeling nothing.
critic.name: Jared Mobarak
publication.name: Jaredmobarak.com

quote: Joaquin Phoenix's certainly mesmerizing, but his hypnotic quality soon wears out thanks to Phillips' overbearing direction. It's an unrelentingly grim and bleak affair from start to finish, it'd be tough to put on a happy face after you watch it.
critic.name: Ruth Maramis
publication.name: FlixChatter Film Blog

quote: Yes, this film is disturbing and violent, but it deals with serious issues. More than anything else about this film, it's Joaquin Phoenix' performance that stands out.
critic.name: Linda and Al Lerner
publication.name: Movies and Shakers

quote: It's less a film than a showcase for the performance; as that, at least, it's pretty good.
critic.name: Sean Collier
publication.name: Pittsburgh Magazine

quote: Truth is, this is not really a groundbreaking exercise in making us sympathize with the Devil. This is not a monster creator on a big screen, it's just familiar plot in grease makeup.
critic.name: Tim Stevens
publication.name: Comicsverse

quote: This movie isn't as intelligent or irreverent as Todd Phillips might think. But it does challenge the conventional structures of the genre and the ideological implications of superhero movies. Flawed and riveting. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Nicolás Ruiz
publication.name: Código espagueti

quote: It is a premise in search of an argument, and, finding none, is content to get by on empty commotion.
critic.name: Tomas Trussow
publication.name: The Lonely Film Critic

quote: Despite finding Joker to be an incredibly unique cinematic experience, the result of craftspeople at the top of their game, the manner in which they successfully capture the nature of the Joker instills far more trepidation than awe.
critic.name: Douglas Davidson
publication.name: Elements of Madness

quote: Joker manages to modernize a character that is carved in the collective imagination by mixing the styles of New Hollywood with a current social criticism, dragging the viewer towards a vortex of emotional setbacks. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Luis Fernando Galván
publication.name: En Filme

quote: While Joker may not break the superhero wheel, it works as a denunciation of a corrupt society in which its members can be as toxic and as aggressive as the people it signals out. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Fernanda Solórzano
publication.name: Letras Libres

quote: A formidable and twisted film. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Javier Ocaña
publication.name: El Pais (Spain)

quote: From his spat-out perspective, the world in which Arthur Fleck struggles to exist is malevolently ugly.
critic.name: Andiee Paviour
publication.name: Nobody's Reading This But Me

quote: "Joker" tries hard to be dark, disturbing, and meaningful. It is dark, but it is sour, superficial and gross.
critic.name: Nell Minow
publication.name: Movie Mom

quote: It demands we think about power, difference and violence in ways we do not necessarily expect a heavily branded mainstream blockbuster to do so.
critic.name: Alexandra Heller-Nicholas
publication.name: Flicks.com.au

quote: If you're feeling insufficiently anxious in your life, "Joker" could be just the ticket. If not, look elsewhere to be entertained.
critic.name: Joe Morgenstern
publication.name: Wall Street Journal

quote: In a sick way, all this controversy might be a boon for Joker, because the movie itself is painfully mediocre and politically dunderheaded.
critic.name: Kristy Puchko
publication.name: Pajiba

quote: "Joker" stays with the viewer, forcing you to consider it more carefully. The picture you'll get is dark - haunting, disturbing and all too real.
critic.name: Greg Maki
publication.name: Star-Democrat (Easton, MD)

quote: A movie that is destined to become a defining moment of the comic-book genre. And that's no joke.
critic.name: Cameron Meier
publication.name: Orlando Weekly

quote: A profoundly upsetting movie that is powerfully constructed. There's a precision to the camerawork, but the images are gritty and dank. It's as if the film stock is rotting away before our eyes.
critic.name: Michael J. Casey
publication.name: Michael J. Cinema

quote: Once again the role of the Joker gives another actor the role of their career. It's dark, non-comic like, and an amazing experience, though not anything like what we've seen from DC before. And in this case, that's a good thing.
critic.name: Bill Watters
publication.name: Aggressive Comix

quote: Phoenix delivers an Oscar-worthy performance in The Joker.
critic.name: Allison Rose
publication.name: FlickDirect

quote: Expertly crafted and features a stunning lead performance, but it's also a morally problematic exercise in cinematic nihilism.
critic.name: Frank Swietek
publication.name: One Guy's Opinion

quote: Whether it's worth seeing depends on your tolerance for glorifying a dangerous mentally ill man breaking bad and becoming a menace to the society that abandoned him. Yup, the joke's on us - all of us. And it's a message pounded home with a sledgehammer.
critic.name: Dana Barbuto
publication.name: The Patriot Ledger

quote: Joker is a bad movie, yes: It's predictable, clichéd, deeply derivative of other, better movies, and overwritten to the point of self-parody.
critic.name: Dana Stevens
publication.name: Slate

quote: The only thing wrong with 'Joker' is the commercial imposition that the main character has to become the Joker at the end. Absent that, it's actually a pretty good movie.
critic.name: Vincent Mancini
publication.name: FilmDrunk

quote: "Joker" is an effective slow burn that takes an iconic villain, humanizes him, and gives the audience an insight to mental illness.
critic.name: Jason Escamilla
publication.name: EskimoTV

quote: There is an Arthur Fleck in all of us. And that thought may just be subconsciously more than many movie-goers can bear.
critic.name: Tom Santilli
publication.name: Movie Show Plus

quote: Believe the hype, ignore the naysayers and savor the year's best movie ... so far.
critic.name: Christian Toto
publication.name: HollywoodInToto.com

quote: Joker has a nasty, oppressive power, and it never falters in its grim, purposeful momentum.
critic.name: Tom Gliatto
publication.name: People Magazine

quote: Mental illness, gun control, society's apathetic decay, the chasm between rich and poor; Joker takes a fatalistic dive into heady issues.
critic.name: Julian Roman
publication.name: MovieWeb

quote: It's hard to say if the muddle "Joker" makes of itself arises from confusion or cowardice, but the result is less a depiction of nihilism than a story about nothing.
critic.name: A.O. Scott
publication.name: New York Times

quote: It is brilliantly performed - you can put the house on Phoenix getting an Oscar nomination, at least - stunningly well staged and disarmingly well written and argued.
critic.name: Graeme Tuckett
publication.name: Stuff.co.nz

quote: Perhaps the bleakest assertion of "Joker" is the one that's hardest to disprove: That the ghastly world Fleck inhabits, and by extension ours, is the one we deserve.
critic.name: John Wenzel
publication.name: Denver Post

quote: It's provocative but sadly, it's also irresponsible in the handling of that material.
critic.name: Akhil Arora
publication.name: Gadgets360

quote: Joker is socially irresponsible at times, but with purpose.
critic.name: Gerald Peary
publication.name: Arts Fuse

quote: Joker is a devastatingly bold, brashly aggressive, truly haunting homage to the clown prince of crime. It stands proud as one of the most troubling, worrisome and delightfully distressing pieces of comic book cinema.
critic.name: Annie Banks
publication.name: Glue Magazine

quote: Phillips and Silver have no interest in how [Arthur] can rid himself of the clutter that corrupts his existence. They're only interested in chaos; however, they don't elevate the chaos into a meaningful narrative, they pander to the audience with it.
critic.name: Michael Calleri
publication.name: Niagara Gazette

quote: Phillips could have made a nip and tuck here or there to shave off run time, but he asks questions about society where no easy answers exist. In that respect, he makes "Joker" very much worth the time and money invested.
critic.name: George M. Thomas
publication.name: Akron Beacon Journal

quote: Joker builds into a statement that's salient and provocative - holding a mirror to real world frustration and the resurgent populism in our midst.
critic.name: Jason Di Rosso
publication.name: ABC News (Australia)

quote: Joker's intellectual commentary is just a cheap costume.
critic.name: Hannah Lodge
publication.name: The Beat

quote: Starring a phenomenal Joaquin Phoenix, it's seriously themed, brilliantly executed and quite extraordinary.
critic.name: Demetrios Matheou
publication.name: The Arts Desk

quote: Phillips made a brilliant choice in casting Phoenix, and then he was smart to know that the actor is so deep inside this role that everything he does, up to and including a homicidal rumba, feels right.
critic.name: Chris Hewitt
publication.name: Minneapolis Star Tribune

quote: I find the whole enterprise wearying and a little ridiculous.
critic.name: Max Weiss
publication.name: Baltimore Magazine

quote: It devotes so much of its energy into not being about a comic book villain that it neglects being about ... much of anything, really.
critic.name: Glen Weldon
publication.name: NPR

quote: In what should come to stand as the finest performance of 2019 - Oscars, here he comes! - Phoenix isolates a void in The Joker between the breaking of the man and the making of a menace to society.
critic.name: Leigh Paatsch
publication.name: Herald Sun (Australia)

quote: Joker is brilliantly done, searingly filmed, and so drenched in its seamy milieu that you can practically feel the roaches skittering under your feet.
critic.name: Kyle Smith
publication.name: National Review

quote: Searing onto the screen as both a revisionist backstory of an iconic villain character and a pointed commentary on the cuddlier aspects of the Marvel Cinematic Universe, the new Joker movie is bold, violent, and unnerving.
critic.name: Jeff York
publication.name: Creative Screenwriting

quote: The physicality and emotional rigor of the part of this evil man are easily met by a seasoned professional such as Phoenix.
critic.name: Deirdre Crimmins
publication.name: HighDef Digest

quote: The huge problem with the film's storytelling is that it insults its audience's intelligence and toys with our perception, treating both as an afterthought.
critic.name: Trey Mangum
publication.name: Shadow and Act

quote: Seems like little more than the bitter vision of an obnoxious, brooding teenager in arthouse clothing, as obvious as the on-the-nose soundtrack cues of seemingly every pop song featuring a clown
critic.name: Pat Padua
publication.name: The DC Line

quote: Joker is the best that comics have brought to the movies in years, but what elevates the material is the impeccable performance of Phoenix. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Benjamín Harguindey
publication.name: EscribiendoCine

quote: Joaquin Phoenix aces the role of 'Joker'.
critic.name: Roger Tennis
publication.name: Cinemaclips.com

quote: A comic-book villain inflicts realistic pain in Todd Phillips' well-made and still-maddening Joker.
critic.name: André Hereford
publication.name: Metro Weekly (Washington, DC)

quote: There's much to commend in Phoenix's performance, and the screenplay by Phillips and Scott Silver allows ample room for Arthur's inner fantasy life.
critic.name: Maria Sciullo
publication.name: Pittsburgh Post-Gazette

quote: In this age of superhero saturation, different is refreshing and daring enough.
critic.name: Mark Dujsik
publication.name: Mark Reviews Movies

quote: "Joker," though, is a calculatedly combustible concoction, designed, like its chaos-creating character, to cause a stir. To provoke and distort. I wish it was as radical as it thinks it is.
critic.name: Jake Coyle
publication.name: Associated Press

quote: The film is a desperate, plaintive cry for help, an indictment of a society that ignores the mentally ill within it, calling for more treatment for those afflicted when a tragedy occurs, only to forget about them once the next news cycle begins.
critic.name: Charles Koplinski
publication.name: Illinois Times

quote: As it turns out, the most shocking thing about Joker is just how thin the whole thing is once you strip away the grim visuals from cinematographer Lawrence Sher and the equally oppressive score by Hildur Guonadottir.
critic.name: Peter Sobczynski
publication.name: eFilmCritic.com

quote: The movie wobbles under the weight of its own self-importance, carrying on as if imparting some sort of serious social commentary while being extremely careful not to actually say anything at all.
critic.name: Sean Burns
publication.name: WBUR’s Arts & Culture

quote: It's DC Comics playing rough, but not rough enough, but maybe that's too much to ask.
critic.name: Josh Kupecki
publication.name: Austin Chronicle

quote: Raw. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Pablo O. Scholz
publication.name: Clarín

quote: [T]he film is more character study than franchise film, a psychologically rich portrait of a mentally ill loner that just happens to take place in a world that will one day yield a cowl-wearing billionaire vigilante.
critic.name: Alistair Harkness
publication.name: Scotsman

quote: While the script makes Arthur pitiable, [Joaquin] Phoenix preserves his humanity... he's good enough to make the movie seem better than it is - but even he can't make his character consistent.
critic.name: Ryan Gilbey
publication.name: New Statesman

quote: The supervillain origin story to beat all origin stories.
critic.name: Peter Howell
publication.name: Toronto Star

quote: The real reason Phillips' "Joker" succeeds is simple: Joaquin Phoenix makes the anti-antihero psycho-saga all his own.
critic.name: Tom Meek
publication.name: Cambridge Day

quote: Todd Phillips pulls his punches, so his film needles the audience, daring you to be upset about it. This is the cinematic equivalent of bullying.
critic.name: Alan Zilberman
publication.name: Washington City Paper

quote: A masterpiece, or irresponsible trash? You decide. Or just step away, and spare yourself the grief. That's probably for the best.
critic.name: Deborah Ross
publication.name: The Spectator

quote: This Joker has a ruined poetry to him that makes his victimhood seem a badge of honor and his homicidal urges seem a just, if horrifying, form of retribution.
critic.name: Ty Burr
publication.name: Boston Globe

quote: That's what makes this film so insidious, the 'Joker' movie might be a far bigger villain than the Joker himself ever was.
critic.name: Sherin Nicole
publication.name: idobi.com

quote: The social commentary of "Joker" is laughably one-dimensional and Phoenix's Fleck isn't that scary. Really, he's more sad than anything.
critic.name: Ross Raihala
publication.name: St. Paul Pioneer Press

quote: [The film] is made with pain and glory and true passion. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Javier Porta Fouz
publication.name: La Nación (Argentina)

quote: Purported to be a significant commentary on the social ills of our time, JOKER only exacerbates the appeal of violence to individuals who are drawn to its dark and disturbing content.
critic.name: Jeanne Kaplan
